Study Information
TITLE:
Replication of a Research Claim from Petersen et al. (2017) in
Cognition
AUTHORS:

Nathan Higgins1
Mary Sanchez1
Jessica Nave-Blodgett1
Joel Snyder1
Melissa Kline2
1 University of Nevada, Las Vegas
2 Center for Open Science, Charlottesville, VA
DESCRIPTION:
The claim selected for replication from Petersen et al. (2017) is
from Experiment 1, in which participants were to report the
identity of a post-masked letter that was presented for varying
exposure durations immediately after an auditory cue or no cue.
Equations based on a theory of visual attention were fit to the data
for each participant (see equations p. 74), separately for cue and
no-cue trials, with the result that the parameter for processing
speed (v) was faster following an auditory cue, compared to no-cue
trials. This reflects the following from the paper’s abstract:
“[P]hasic auditory alertness affects visual perception by increasing
the visual processing speed and lowering the threshold of conscious
perception (Experiment 1).”
Using the equations shown on page 74, for each condition (no cue,
85 dB cue), v and t0 parameters were estimated separately for each
subject by a maximum-likelihood estimation using the Nelder-Mead
simplex optimization algorithm. To improve the estimation of
parameters, a high-threshold guessing model was introduced, which
assumes that with a certain probability, subjects guess randomly
among the 20 letters if they fail to encode the presented letter into

visual short term memory. Paired t tests were used to compare
these parameter values between conditions. This analysis yielded
that there was faster processing speed v, t(27) = 4.71, p < 0.001,
dz = 0.89, and a lower perceptual threshold t0, t(27) = 3.52, p =
0.002, dz = 0.67, when an 85 dB SPL cue is presented prior to the
letter, compared to when no cue was present.
HYPOTHESIS:
After fitting the model to each participant’s probabilities of correct
response as a function of exposure duration to the 85 dB SPL cue
and no-cue trials separately, the values on parameter v will be
larger (i.e., steeper slope) for cue trials than for no-cue trials.
Design Plan
STUDY TYPE:
Experiment: This is a purely within-subjects design study in which
different conditions (e.g., cue vs. no-cue, duration of target) are
quasi-randomly manipulated on each trial for each participant.
BLINDING:
No blinding is reported in the original paper; all conditions are
within subject and data collection is administered with a computer
script.
For the replication, there will be no deliberate blinding. This is a

within-subjects experiment and it will be apparent to participants
when the alerting cues or lack of cue are occurring prior to the
target stimulus.
STUDY DESIGN:
This is a fully within-subjects experiment with several manipulated
variables. However, for the purpose of the key statistical test, this
experiment has only one independent variable (cue vs. no-cue),
which will be assessed for its effect on two theoretically-derived
variables, processing speed (v) and perceptual threshold (t0). The
other key independent variable will be target duration, which can
take on values from 10-80 ms in 10 ms steps, and will be used for
estimating the theoretically-derived variables using a computational
model.
RANDOMIZATION:
The distribution of trial order is specified in Question 12 (data
collection procedure). This is a purely within-subjects experiment
and several variables are quasi-randomly chosen on each trial.
These variables include cue vs. no-cue, target duration, target
identity, inter-trial interval, and cue-to-target interval.
Sampling Plan
EXISTING DATA:
Registration prior to creation of data: As of the date of submission
of this research plan for preregistration, the data have not yet been

collected, created, or realized.
EXPLANATION OF EXISTING DATA: N/A
DATA COLLECTION PROCEDURES:
Participants will be recruited from the UNLV Psychology subject
pool or from the local community and receive course credits or $10
per hour, respectively. All will be 18-35 years old and have normal
or corrected-to-normal vision and will have normal hearing as
assessed by pure-tone audiometry from 200-2000 Hz using a GSI-17
audiometer (<30 dB HL at each tested frequency).
During the experimental trials, participants will view visual stimuli
on a 21” CRT computer monitor with a 100 Hz refresh rate and
listen to auditory stimuli over high-quality speakers to the left and
right of the participant, with their head on chin rest to maintain
viewing distance of 65 cm. Before each trial, participants will look
directly at a black fixation cross (0.44 x 0.44 deg of visual angle) on
a grey background for a quasi-randomly selected amount of time
(1600-4000 ms). Next, the 85 dB SPL auditory cue will be played
for 200 ms on one-third of the trials or no cue will be presented for
200 ms on two-thirds of trials, followed by the fixation cross for a
quasi-randomly selected amount of time (200-470 ms). Then, a
target letter (Arial font size 68 or a font size that results in a letter
taking up about 2.0 x 2.5 deg of visual angle) will be presented for
10-80 ms 3.4 deg of visual angle the right or to the left of the center
of the fixation cross, followed by a 500 ms black and dark grey
masking stimuli composed of letter fragments (each taking up 3.3 x
3.3 deg of visual angle) covering both possible target locations.
After the masking stimuli, the screen will be blank and participants
will type in the letter on the keyboard corresponding to the identity
of the target they observe with no time constraints if they are
“fairly certain” they saw the target. If they are not certain, they
simply will initiate a new trial without making a response. After
initiating a new trial, the screen will provide feedback about
whether their answer is correct (‘*’) or not (‘—’) for 500 ms.

Participants will complete 2 sessions of 480 trials, with each session
containing 12 blocks of 40 trials. Participants will be encouraged to
take short breaks between blocks.
SAMPLE SIZE:
The initial target for participant recruitment is 31 participants.
Given an expected attrition rate of 20%, this will lead to a study
sample size of at least 26 participants. If a statistically significant
effect is not observed after the first round of data collection, a
second round will begin. The second round of data collection will
sample an additional 36 participants for a pooled sample after
attrition of 56 participants.
SAMPLE SIZE RATIONALE:
Power calculations were done in accordance with the guidelines of
the Social Sciences Replication Project (SSRP). The first round of
data collection achieves 90% power to detect 75% of the original
effect size. The pooled sample, if necessary after testing the effect
on the first round of data, achieves 90% power to detect 50% of the
original effect size.
The power analysis for this paper can be found here.
STOPPING RULE:
The planned sample size is 26; accounting for 20% attrition (due to
reasons stated below under Data Exclusions), the initial recruitment
target is 31 participants. After achieving that latter sample, planned
analyses will be run. If a significant effect is found, sampling stops.

If a significant effect is not found, a second round of data collection
will collect data from 36 additional participants (with a target
sample of 30 with 20% attrition), for a pooled sample after attrition
of 56. Sampling will stop after the second round of data collection
regardless of a significant effect.
Variables
MANIPULATED VARIABLES:
The main independent variables will be 1) how long the target is
presented on the screen (10, 20, 30, 40, 50, 60, 70, or 80 ms), and
2) whether an 85 dB SPL auditory cue or no cue is presented prior
to the target. Additional variables that will be manipulated but are
not empirically or theoretically important are the identity of the
target letter (ABDEFGHJKLMNOPRSTVXZ), the pitch of the
auditory cue (500 or 900 Hz), the intertrial interval (ranging from
1600 to 4000 ms in time steps of 200 ms, but with more short
intervals such that the expected interval was 2000 ms), and the cue-
to-target onset asynchrony (ranging from 200 to 470 ms in time
steps of 30 ms, but with more short intervals such that the expected
interval was 244 ms).
MEASURED VARIABLES:
The empirical dependent variable will be probability of correctly
reporting the presence of the target, but this variable will only be
used to calculate theoretically-derived dependent variables and for
graphing data. The theoretically-derived dependent variables that
will be used for statistical tests are processing speed and perceptual
threshold, estimated for each participant with equations from
Bundesen’s (1990) Theory of Visual Attention, with maximum-
likelihood estimation using the Nelder-Mead simplex optimization
algorithm in Matlab.

INDICES:
Each participant’s full dataset for each condition is fit to a
mathematical model of visual attention, resulting in two parameter
values which are compared in the focal analysis.
Participants’ response functions for the Cue and NoCue conditions
will be compared by fitting a non-linear function that estimates the
probability of correctly reporting a single letter for a given exposure
duration. More specifically, this function estimates the probability
of identifying object x into visual short-term memory and is
expressed as
p = 1-exp(-v*(t-t0)) + exp(-v(t-t0))*pg*1/20
for durations that exceed the threshold; estimates for durations sub-
threshold will be set to pg*1/20. The first part of the equation (1-
exp(-v*(t-t0))) estimates the probability of a correct report, the
second part of the equation accounts for the probability of a correct
(1 out of 20) guess (referred to as pg*1/20 in Petersen et al.,
Equation 3). The optimization algorithm will fit this function to the
observed data for each participant for each condition by finding the
parameters corresponding to v (processing speed, or slope) and t0
(threshold, or maximum duration that does not exceed chance), and
pg that minimize deviation from the observed data. Model fitting
will be conducted in Matlab using a routine that uses maximum-
likelihood to estimate the parameters for v, t0 and pg. The
fminsearch function utilizes the Nelder-Mead simplex optimization
algorithm as in the original study, and initial estimates of 0, 0.02,
and 0.5 for t0, 20, 50, 100 for v and 0, 0.5 and 1 for pg will be
input as starting points for the routine to make sure to search the
entire parameter space for a global maximum.
The estimated parameters for processing speed (v) and threshold
(t0) will be used to compare the No cue and 85 dB cue conditions
(cf. Petersen et al., Fig 1a), using paired t-tests. Measures of the
Variance Explained for each condition will be extracted from the

data by squaring the correlation coefficients calculated between the
modeled response function and the observed data from each
subject.
Analysis Plan
STATISTICAL MODELS:
The analysis script for this replication is available here.
Paired t tests will be used to test for faster processing speed v and a
lowered perceptual threshold t0 when a 85 dB SPL cue is presented
prior to the letter, compared to when no cue is presented.
TRANSFORMATIONS:
See the “Indices” section above.
INFERENCE CRITERIA:
For this replication attempt, this criteria is met by values for
parameter v that are larger (i.e., steeper slope) and lower t0 for cue
trials than for no cue trials (within subjects), as measured by paired
t tests with p < 0.05, two tailed.
DATA EXCLUSIONS:
If a participant fails to complete the entire experiment, produces

data that do not show the expected effect of monotonically better
target identification at longer target durations (needed for v and t0
parameter estimation), or there is an equipment malfunction, the
participant’s data will be excluded and a new participant will be
run to replace the original participant’s data, in order to ensure that
at least the planned number of 26 participants have usable data.
MISSING DATA:
See the “Data Exclusions” section above.
EXPLORATORY ANALYSIS: Bayesian versions of the t tests may be
used to estimate evidence for the experimental and null hypotheses.
Other
DEVIATIONS FROM THE ORIGINAL STUDY:
The main deviations might include participants’ age/gender
distributions and some of the specific makes/models of equipment
used (e.g., chin rest, speakers, monitor), but these variables are not
expected to have a substantial impact on the findings.

